## Context tree

Per-area conventions live in nested `AGENTS.md` nodes, each paired with a one-line `CLAUDE.md` (`@AGENTS.md`) so Claude Code's descendant walker finds them:

| Node | Covers |
|---|---|
| `docs/plans/AGENTS.md` | plan lifecycle + conventions |
| `plugins/{{ plugin_name }}/skills/AGENTS.md` | skill authoring rules |
| `scripts/AGENTS.md` | validators + CI |

The `context-tree` skill maintains these nodes; `scripts/tree/guard.mjs` enforces the pair convention.

## Codex plan agents

The plan contract has five exact owners: `plan-workspace` bootstraps, migrates, audits, or explicitly refreshes the workspace; public `plan-creator` drafts, self-reviews, and commits one previously nonexistent plan; public `plan-manager` owns every existing-plan operation—including guarded `publish <slug> as an issue` / `--issues` GitHub issue publication—review orchestration, prepared-request and candidate-commitment commits, terminal-family validation, receipt, and lifecycle write; internal `plan-reviewer` returns sealed-bundle evidence; and internal `plan-repairer` returns one exact accepted-blocker patch or `cannot_repair`. Only `.codex/agents/plan-manager.toml` and `.codex/agents/plan-reviewer.toml` exist as repo-local wrappers; the other three skills run without wrappers. For creation, manager proves the canonical path is missing and routes to creator, creator returns the closed `PlanCreatedV1` handoff, and main context may separately invoke manager review with lifecycle intent `none`. Current schema 6 commits and reads back the exact prepared request before controller construction, then commits and reads back each candidate's exact-600 dispatch commitment before spawn. Repair advancement atomically removes the round-one request/commitment before a separate round-two prepared-request commit. Only the current user authorizes abandonment; main-context manager alone may persist that exact-byte authorization or a source-plan-bound config abort. It validates reducer output with `validateReviewTerminalFamily({currentPlanBytes,parentPlanBytes})` before commit and again on the committed child plus its exact single parent. StateV2 embeds the exact active source state, and both terminal families are disjoint, receiptless, seriesless, nonretryable, and apply-ineligible. Current schema 6 uses one `gpt-5.6-sol`/high/Standard primary reviewer, with Claude Fable/high then Opus/xhigh as availability-only fallbacks. Main-context manager alone dispatches review, reconciles findings, writes persisted orchestration and receipts, applies lifecycle, and may call repairer once for the complete accepted independently reproduced blocking set. Reviewer remains evidence-only; repairer remains patch-only and neither can commit or abandon. Review has one full round plus at most one changed-input repair round; Session Relay is invalid evidence. Historical schemas 1–5 are validation-only and retain their exact persisted meanings.

Planning and review are proportional. A clear, low-risk change describable as one concrete diff with one bounded acceptance path is implemented directly; simple one-commit work bypasses the plan skills. Use a canonical plan for multi-commit work, scheduling, cold handoff, an unresolved approach, a cross-subsystem or public-contract change, destructive or security-sensitive work, or an explicit user request. Canonical multi-commit plans retain one independent lifecycle review. Never create a placeholder plan merely to unlock review, and never automatically create or review a plan after scaffold generation; review runs only when explicitly requested or required by an existing plan's lifecycle gate.

Historical `plan-improver` is not a live skill; `plan-repairer` returns one exact patch or `cannot_repair`, and `plan-manager` alone validates, applies, and persists the result.

Plan authoring, review, repair, receipt, and lifecycle-only work runs plan-structure checks only: frontmatter, parser, hash, plan-only commit, and read-back checks. It never runs an implementation acceptance command, build, lint, typecheck, test suite, or CI. After code changes, run the smallest acceptance reproduction or smoke check plus directly affected tests. Expand to dependent or representative consumers only for shared harness, configuration, generated, public-contract, security, or release surfaces, or after a concrete targeted failure. Run the final repository gate once only when project policy requires it for the final implementation tree.

Use this manager routing table without introducing another machine schema:

|Observed condition|Owner and next action|Forbidden action|
|---|---|---|
|No plan identity; clear low-risk direct task|main implements and runs targeted verification|create/review/repair a canonical plan|
|New canonical plan requested/required|creator drafts, self-reviews once, returns `PlanCreatedV1`|automatic manager review|
|Planned/scheduled explicit review or lifecycle start/fire|manager runs the existing bounded schema-6 operation|more than one full + one repair round|
|`ongoing`; only catalog/generated-manifest/external snapshot/pin/hash/count changed; nine authority boundaries unchanged|implementation rebinds observed execution inputs and reruns the failed gate once|begin/prepare/dispatch/repair plan review|
|Goal, scope, affected paths, safety authority, budget/resources, architecture/interfaces, acceptance contract, lifecycle intent, or settled user decision changed|plain turn-terminal response to block and explicitly amend; later review the amended blocked plan|infer amendment, create orchestration evidence, or review stale plan|
|Ambiguous pre-review drift|plain turn-terminal response naming the unresolved boundary and allowed amendment action|emit orchestration `NeedsUserAction` or default to review|
|Exact caller-held schema-6 result|manager settles immediately through the atomic family reducer; pass may consume one eligible intent, non-pass stops|fresh bundle/reviewer/repairer|
|Attempt-1 retryable `stopped` plus exact current-user authorization|begin same-key attempt 2 once|automatic retry, attempt 3, or retry from `stuck`/nonretryable state|
|Other terminal result for the same `(phase,intent_group,input_sha256)`|render/stop or consume the one eligible intent|reprepare, redispatch, or metadata reset|
|Completion requested after implementation|completion review only|another draft review|

Execution rebind is operation-local: one rebind plus one rerun of the failed command. If observations do not change or the same mismatch remains, return one plain turn-terminal user action; never repeat rebind or open review.

`turn-terminal` is the final user response for this turn: no later tool, subagent, review, repair, retry, reprepare, plan, or lifecycle action. `invocation-terminal` is the final result of the current child skill or wrapper; main may consume it in the same turn. Schema 6 has no candidate fallback: every reviewer output or failure is invocation-terminal and returns once.

Every completed main manager operation—successful settlement, intent application, no-op result, or user action—is turn-terminal. Reviewer outputs, repairer results, `PlanCreatedV1`, and delegated wrapper handoffs are invocation-terminal. Direct helper returns inside main are intermediate.

An exact caller-held schema-6 result settles immediately through the atomic family reducer: pass may consume one eligible intent, while non-pass stops. It never creates a fresh bundle or dispatches a reviewer or repairer. Any other terminal result for the same `(phase,intent_group,input_sha256)` stops or consumes the one eligible intent without reprepare, redispatch, or metadata reset. Attempt 2 begins only from an attempt-1 retryable `stopped` result plus exact current-user authorization; it is never automatic, never attempt 3, and never available from `stuck` or nonretryable state. Completion requested after implementation routes only to completion review, never another draft review.

Emit concise progress text only, not `PlanProgressV1`: `Plan review: attempt A/2, round R/2, stage <full|repair|settling>`. Update only on stage changes; there is no candidate fallback or same-stage relaunch.

Every prepared request and exact-600 dispatch commitment is written/read back
in a separate plan-only commit before launch. `buildReviewerArgv` is
derivation-only. `dispatchCommittedReviewer` is the sole consuming process
boundary: it reads exact current-HEAD, single-parent plan-only Git bytes,
matches expected request/commitment hashes and actual proposed
`orchestrator_tool/600` config/committed argv, then calls trusted
`controllerAdapter.dispatch` once with committed values. Invalid or substituted
paths call it zero times,
and no argv/commitment result is reusable launch authorization.

Schema 6 keeps the policy shape
`{schema:6,role:"primary",fallback:"none",max_rounds:2,candidates:[runtimeCurrent],provenance:{role:"skill_default",fallback:"skill_default",max_rounds:"skill_default",candidates:"runtime_global"}}`.
The sole candidate exactly matches `request.author` company/tool/model/effort;
Codex additionally uses `service_tier: "default"` and Claude omits it. Each
commitment binds candidate index `0`, `prior_attempts: []`, and the exact JCS
hash of that empty array. No provider/model fallback or Session Relay review is
allowed.

Before commitment, manager verifies the sealed bundle path/digest and prepares
a safe schema-6 Codex workspace. Commitment deep-copies its record/hash; Claude
uses null. The gate independently rechecks bundle plus workspace root/path,
owner/mode, non-symlink, and sentinel, then rederives argv. Proposed config
comparison covers only candidate index, argv/hash, and timeout fields.

The gate also compares current worktree plan bytes byte-for-byte to
`git show <committedPlanCommit>:<planPath>` (or enforces equivalent path
cleanliness); uncommitted post-commit drift calls the adapter zero times.

Each authorized invocation launches one newly created reviewer. Round 2 exists
only for changed canonical input after repair and launches another new reviewer;
never resume the round-one handle or session. The sole unchanged-input exception
is the existing explicitly authorized retryable attempt 2, which also launches a
new reviewer with the same runtime-current identity.

Terminal reducer output is checked with
`validateReviewTerminalFamily({currentPlanBytes,parentPlanBytes})` before
commit and again from the committed child and exact single-parent plan blobs.
Administrative abandonment is source-plan/state-bound and persists canonical
base64 plus SHA-256 of the current user's exact UTF-8 authorization bytes.

Implementation evidence binds to the implementation tree plus `affected_paths`.
The bound implementation identity is SHA-256 of compact JCS over sorted
`affected_paths` entries. Each entry binds the exact repo-relative path, Git
kind/mode, and blob SHA-256, or an explicit tombstone for absence. Exclude the
plan/orchestration path unless it is itself an affected implementation path.
Plan-only state, request, commitment, and lifecycle commits reuse prior green
implementation evidence while implementation bytes are unchanged; they still
run machine-family validation and plan read-back, never implementation commands.
Any affected-path byte, mode, kind, or presence change invalidates reuse and
requires fresh targeted implementation evidence. Completion consumes the bound
evidence when the affected-path digest is unchanged and requests only missing
contract proof; it does not duplicate a final repository gate. Release and
final implementation gates remain authoritative when project policy requires them.

CI evidence reuse is the churn/performance fix; it never collapses authorization
commits. Active-state, prepared-request, and dispatch-commitment commits MUST
remain separate because each later artifact is derived only after committed
read-back of its predecessor. Combining them atomically is forbidden.

If an active plan changes the canonical review controller, manager, or reviewer
mechanism used for its own completion, same-checkout self-dispatch is forbidden.
Return `NeedsUserAction`; require an independent trusted released or pinned
bootstrap reviewer path, or a later fresh session. Never repair, reseal, or
replace orchestration in place to bypass this boundary. `stopped`, `stuck`, and
attempt-2 failure return `NeedsUserAction` without automatic reprepare or retry.

## Tool-agnostic rules

- Run `corepack enable && pnpm install --frozen-lockfile` once, then `node scripts/tree/guard.mjs` and `node scripts/skills/guard.mjs plugins/{{ plugin_name }}/skills` before commit
- Skill bodies stay ≤500 lines per agentskills.io spec (sweet spot 80–310)
- Manifest versions stay in lockstep across both `plugin.json`s and both marketplace catalogs
